{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503031"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:53:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:53:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1925"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1925"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.35,0.06,0.08,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1925"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80372"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1925"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1925"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65641"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1877"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"11615"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8774"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27469"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44349"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80372"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of fever, headache, and confusion. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He recently returned from a camping trip in northern Australia. He works as an accountant and does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.4\u00b0C. He is disoriented to time and place with inappropriate behaviour. He has neck stiffness and photophobia. The remainder of the neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECerebrospinal fluid analysis reveals elevated white cells with lymphocyte predominance, normal glucose, and elevated protein, consistent with viral meningoencephalitis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative virus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ross River virus","Murray Valley virus","Barmah Forest virus","Zika virus","Dengue virus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of encephalitis: fever, headache, and altered mental status. The presence of neck stiffness, photophobia and CSF findings consistent with viral meningoencephalitis confirms the diagnosis. Given the patient\u0027s recent camping history in Australia, arboviral causes must be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMurray Valley virus\u003C/strong\u003E is an important cause of encephalitis in Australia, particularly in rural and remote areas. It is transmitted by mosquitoes and can cause severe neurological disease. The presentation with meningoencephalitis, recent outdoor exposure, and geographical location make this the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERoss River virus\u003C/strong\u003E, while common in Australia, typically causes polyarthritis, rash, and fatigue. It rarely causes neurological manifestations and meningoencephalitis would be extremely unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBarmah Forest virus\u003C/strong\u003E presents similarly to Ross River virus with arthralgia, myalgia, and rash. Neurological involvement is not a typical feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZika virus\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes a mild illness with rash, fever, and arthralgia. While it can have neurological complications (particularly Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome), meningoencephalitis would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDengue virus\u003C/strong\u003E causes fever, severe headache, and myalgias. While neurological complications can occur, they are uncommon, and the absence of characteristic features like severe muscle pain and rash makes this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Murray Valley encephalitis virus is an important cause of viral encephalitis in Australia, particularly in people with outdoor exposure.","The classic triad of encephalitis is fever, headache and altered mental status.","CSF analysis showing viral meningoencephalitis with a compatible clinical picture should prompt consideration of arboviral causes in Australia."],"references":["Said S, Kang M. Viral encephalitis. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470162/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65641"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1925"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65641"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-20T14:58:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-20T14:59:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1925"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80372"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position"